Polish Stocks: Cinema City, Orlen, Pekao, PKO Bank, PZU Move

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i
-- 
2011-03-04T13:48:40Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-04/polish-stocks-cinema-city-orlen-pekao-pko-bank-pzu-move.html
  Poland ’s WIG20 Index climbed for a
third day, increasing 22.20, or 0.8 percent, to 2,785.09 at 2:42
p.m. in Warsaw and heading for the highest close in six weeks.
The measure has gained 4.2 percent this week.  The following are among the most active stocks on the  Warsaw Stock Exchange  today. Stock symbols follow company names.    Bank Pekao SA (PEO)  , majority-owned by UniCredit SpA,
led gains among Polish financial shares, climbing 4.2 zloty, or
2.5 percent, to 172.1 zloty. PKO Bank Polski SA (PKO PW), the
country’s biggest bank, increased 0.38 zloty, or 0.9 percent, to
43.73 zloty and  BRE Bank SA (BRE)  , a unit of Commerzbank AG,
added 3.6 zloty, or 1.1 percent, to 323.7 zloty.  Polish banks’ combined net income rose 28 percent to 1.09
billion zloty ($380 million) in January from the same month a
year earlier, the country’s financial market regulator said in a
statement published on its website yesterday.    Cinema City International NV (CCI)   jumped 2.12 zloty, or
6 percent, to 37.5 zloty, heading for the biggest one-day gain
since December.  Central Europe ’s largest movie-theater operator
was upgraded to “buy” from “hold” at UniCredit SpA.  PKN Orlen SA (PKN PW), Poland’s biggest oil company, gained
1.4 zloty, or 2.9 percent, to 49.1 zloty, heading for the
highest close in seven weeks. Oil rose as unrest in  Libya 
renewed concern supply disruptions may spread to the Middle
East.  PZU SA (PZU PW), Poland’s biggest insurer, added as much as
1.8 percent to 354 zloty and last traded 0.9 percent higher at
351 zloty. KBC Securities recommended buying PZU shares in new
coverage, citing the company’s “strong solvency and dividend
payment capacity.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
Pawel Kozlowski in Warsaw 
